# 1. Area Chart 
# Create an area chart showing the average petal length for each species. 
#  X-axis: Species 
#  Y-axis: Average Petal Length (cm) 
#  Add legend and gridlines (major and minor). 
#  Set the legend position to the bottom-right corner. 
#  Add a legend title "Species" and set the legend font size to 12.
#  Title: "Average Petal Length by Species" 

df = pd.read_csv('Iris.csv')
avd_petal_len = df.groupby('Species')['PetalLengthCm'].mean()
plt.fill_between(avd_petal_len.index, avd_petal_len.values, alpha=0.5)
plt.title("Average Petal Length by Species")
plt.xlabel("Species")
plt.ylabel("Average Petal Length (cm)")
plt.legend(title="Species", fontsize=12, loc='lower right')
plt.grid(which='both', linestyle='--', linewidth=0.5)
plt.show()

# 2. Bubble Chart 
# X-axis: Sepal Length 
# Y-axis: Sepal Width 
# Bubble size: Petal Length 
# Bubble color: Species 
# Title: "Iris Flower Features" 

x = df['SepalLengthCm']
y = df['SepalWidthCm']
sizes = df['PetalLengthCm'] * 100  # Scale bubble size for better
color = df['Species'].astype('category').cat.codes  # Convert species to numeric codes for coloring
plt.scatter(x, y, s=sizes, c=color, alpha=0.5)
plt.title("Iris Flower Features")
plt.xlabel("Sepal Length (cm)")
plt.ylabel("Sepal Width (cm)")
plt.legend(*plt.gca().get_legend_handles_labels(), title="Species", fontsize=12, loc='upper right')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

# Heat Map 
# o Create a correlation heatmap for all numeric features. 
# o Title: "Heatmap of Iris features" 

numeric_df = df.select_dtypes(include=[np.number])
correlation_matrix = numeric_df.corr()
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.heatmap(correlation_matrix,annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', linewidths=0.5)
plt.title("Heatmap of Iris features")
plt.show()

#  Box Plot 
# o Create box plots for petal length by species. 
# o Title: "Petal Length Distribution by Species" 
# o Create box plots showing the distribution of petal length for each species. 
# o Clearly represent the median, first quartile (Q1), third quartile (Q3), and the interquartile 
# range (IQR). 
# o Display outliers using distinct marker symbols for easy identification. 
# o Use different colors for each species to ensure clear visual distinction.

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.boxplot(x='Species', y='PetalLengthCm', data=df, palette='Set1')
plt.title("Petal Length Distribution by Species")
plt.xlabel("Species")
plt.ylabel("Petal Length (cm)")
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

#  Pair Plot 
# o Create pairwise scatter plots between all numeric features. 
# o Create pairwise scatter plots between all numeric features of the Iris dataset: Sepal 
# Length, Sepal Width, Petal Length and Petal Width. 
# o Display feature-to-feature relationships across all possible combinations. 
# o Use a consistent axis scale for all subplots to ensure fair visual comparison. Apply 
# uniform marker style and size for visual consistency. 
# o Use different colors for different species to enable class-wise visual separation. 
# o Maintain color consistency for each species across all subplots. 

plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
sns.pairplot(df ,hue='Species', palette='Set1')
plt.suptitle("Pairwise Scatter Plots of Iris Features", y=1.02)
plt.show()
